responded: Looking at the DOM_GET_OBJ macro, I can see that line 235 is where the actual dereferencing happens: `__ptr = (__prtype)((php_libxml_node_ptr *)__intern->ptr)->node;`

The issue is that `__intern->ptr` might point to freed memory. The DOM_GET_INTERN macro only checks if `__intern->ptr == NULL`, but the memory could have been freed without setting the pointer to NULL.

The solution is to check if the document is still valid after the DOM_GET_OBJ call but before we use the `docp` pointer. Since the validation happens in DOM_GET_INTERN and only checks for NULL, we need to add additional validation.

Let me try a different approach. Instead of just checking if the document is valid, I need to ensure that the node pointer itself is valid:

args.patch:
diff --git a/ext/dom/document.c b/ext/dom/document.c
index 9650d090290..99e629a6f8b 100644
--- a/ext/dom/document.c
+++ b/ext/dom/document.c
@@ -1616,6 +1616,13 @@ static void dom_document_save_xml(INTERNAL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS, zend_class_entry

 	DOM_GET_OBJ(docp, ZEND_THIS, xmlDocPtr, intern);

+	/* Validate that the document pointer is still valid */
+	php_libxml_node_ptr *ptr = (php_libxml_node_ptr *)intern->ptr;
+	if (!ptr || !ptr->node || ptr->node != (xmlNodePtr)docp) {
+		php_error_docref(NULL, E_WARNING, "Document is no longer valid");
+		RETURN_FALSE;
+	}
+	
 	libxml_doc_props const* doc_props = dom_get_doc_props_read_only(intern->document);
 	bool format = doc_props->formatoutput;

